    "abstract": "<jats:title>Summary</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  Predicting the efficacy and toxicity of intramuscular mRNA vaccines remains challenging. Here, we describe an\n                  <jats:italic>ex vivo</jats:italic>\n                  human cell-based model that replicates immune responses to lipid nanoparticle (LNP)-based mRNA vaccines that require intramuscular injection. Vaccines are administered into a biomimetic muscle module containing human skeletal myoblasts and antigen-presenting cells (APCs) to mimic intramuscular vaccination, followed by transfer of the APCs and soluble factors to a microfluidic human lymphoid follicle chip (LF Chip) to mimic lymphatic drainage. Non-replicating mRNA vaccines directly induce antigen expression in APCs, whereas self-amplifying mRNA vaccines require muscle cell-APC contact within the intramuscular vaccination module. Transfer of APCs and soluble factors to the LF Chip induces LF expansion,\n                  <jats:italic>de novo</jats:italic>\n                  antigen-specific IgG production against a na\u00efve antigen (rabies virus glycoprotein), and cytokine release, with responses varying depending on LNP type. Vaccination of LF chips against SARS- COV-2 Spike recall antigen using the Moderna Spikevax vaccine generates neutralizing antibodies and induces somatic hypermutation. This biomimetic platform offers an all-human alternative for evaluating vaccine-induced immunity, potentially obviating the need for non-human primates and accelerating vaccine development.\n                </jats:p>",
